<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE -- Pierre Schori, head of the European Union (EU)
observer mission in Zimbabwe's parliamentary election, Saturday
said voting started peacefully in most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
There were a few cases of violence in some areas countrywide,
Schori told reporters in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said some observers in certain areas in the country had
reported that people were being prevented from voting by groups of
youths. He could not name the areas which had experienced such
cases. (Zimbabwe-Election-Violence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The judge presiding over the trial of 13 Iranian Jews
accused of spying for Israel has formally closed the case Saturday,
with the court verdict to be issued within a week, said a
judiciary official.
</P>
<P>
The judge closed the files of 13 Jewish and four Muslim
suspects accused of spying for Israel after receiving a response
to the last court query, said Hossein Ali Amiri, the head of
judiciary in Iran's southern Fars Province. (Iran-Jews-Trial)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) disclosed
Saturday that it had received five conditions presented by the
Philippine government for the extension of the June 30 deadline
for a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
MILF spokesman Eid Kabalu said that the MILF leadership could
not submit its comment yet, as the matter has to be discussed
first by its leaders, the Philippine News Agency reported. (
Philippines-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- At least six bomb blasts hit the southern Philippine
city of General Santos on Saturday evening, killing at least one
person and injuring 36 others, according to a TV report.
</P>
<P>
The report said one woman was killed in the series of bombings,
which took place at about 18:30 local time (10:30 GMT). A second
person can not be confirmed dead, said the ABS-CBN News Channel.
(Philippines-bombings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Muslim extremist group Abu Sayyaf Saturday
released one of the 21 hostages it held captive on the Jolo island
in the southern Philippine province of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
The freed hostage is a 29-year-old Malaysian called Zulkurmain
Bin Hashim, and he is now under the custody of Robert Aventajado,
government chief negotiator tasked to secure the release of the 21
mostly foreign hostages, the ABS-CBN News Channel reported. (
Philippine-Hostage) 
</P>
</TEXT>
