<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Reports Rapid Growth in Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Imports and exports in this
largest city in southwest China grew sharply in the first five
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics showed that the city imported 342 million US
dollars-worth of goods and exported 284 million US dollars-worth
of goods in the period, up 67 percent and 84 percent, respectively,
on the figures for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
General trade imports through Chongqing port reached 228
million US dollars-worth, double the figure for the same period of
1999; general trade exports increased nearly 50 percent to 109
million US dollars-worth.
</P>
<P>
Authorities attribute the growth of foreign trade to a vastly
improved investment environment and the improvement of local ports
and transportation conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Servants' Strike Continues in Nigeria's Lagos State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Government offices remained closed
and state- owned firms paralyzed Saturday as the civil servants'
strike in Lagos State in southwestern Nigeria entered its third
day.
</P>
<P>
The state government and strikers maintain their own tough
stance over the minimum monthly wage, with the government sticking
to its offer of 5, 500 naira ( 55 U.S. dollars), and the state
employees insisting on 7,500 naira (75 dollars) given to employees
of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of different minimum wages for federal and
state workers by the central government on May 1 triggered the
crisis, which threatens to erupt into another nationwide strike
as workers in the country' s 36 states demand between 6,500 naira
(65 dollars) and 7,500 (75 dollars) naira minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
A meeting in the capital Abuja Thursday between state governors
and representatives of the labor group, the Nigeria Labour
Congress (NLC), failed to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Lagos State government Friday attempted to break the ranks
of the workers by enforcing an earlier directive that the workers
return to their desks or be fired.
</P>
<P>
In compliance, many workers reported at their various offices
to register their names, but they were later chased out of the
premises by officials of the Council of Industrial Union (COIU),
the umbrella body for all labor unions in the state public
service.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, the government declared the union illegal and
expressed the hope that the strike would soon end.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure that by Monday or Tuesday, everything would have been
100 percent normal," governor of the state Rauf Tinubu said.
</P>
<P>
But COIU chairman Ayodele Akele, who addressed the workers
Friday, asked them not to be intimidated by the government's
action, saying that it was impossible for the government to break
the strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Army Denies Coup Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Army Saturday described
as malicious and injurious a report alleging that some officers
were holding secret meetings with a view to toppling the country's
civilian government.
</P>
<P>
The statement was in response to a report carried by a
Lagos-based radio station saying that officers within the ranks of
colonels and majors were holding secret meetings in Makurdi in the
middle belt, Calabar and Port Harcourt, both in the southeast,
with the intention of overthrowing President Olusegun Obasanjo's
one-year-old government.
</P>
<P>
The army is taking the issue seriously because Nigeria is
widely regarded as coup prone, with more than half a dozen
successful military coups since 1966, in addition to a host of
unsuccessful bids.
</P>
<P>
The army has ruled Africa's most populous nation for 29 of its
39 years after independence, and the country only returned to
civilian rule on May, 29, 1999 after 15 years of unbroken military
rule.
</P>
<P>
Successive military dictators have plundered the economy and
damaged the national psyche with unbridled corruption and human
rights violations, making Nigerians to be very alert to actions
that could bring back the soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
