<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jail Protest Spreads in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A jail protest by inmates protesting
conditions and calling for amnesties spread from the north to the
south of Italy Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In Naples, prisoners in the Poggioreale and Secondigliano jails
rattled the bars of their cells and shouted slogans during the
night and into the morning, taking their cue from counterparts in
the northeastern city of Trieste Saturday, who waved burning
sheets and threw flaming paper out of their cell windows.
</P>
<P>
The Trieste inmates demanded to meet the prison warden and,
like the others, called for an amnesty for many crimes. Like most
Italian jails, Trieste is over-crowded, with 210 inmates for its
150 places.
</P>
<P>
But the extent of the over-capacity in Italy's teeming jails is
estimated to be around 30,000. The situation is made worse by grim
living conditions and the fact that a large percentage of the
prison population has AIDS.
</P>
<P>
There were similar protests, all without violent incidents, in
the Genoese prison Pontedecimo and in Bergamo east of Milan.
</P>
<P>
A half-hour protest took place Sunday afternoon in another
northern city, Trento, while in Bologna a group of inmates started
a hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
The protests have taken the political world by surprise,
especially after the recent approval of a reform that would
improve living conditions.
</P>
<P>
Italian Justice Minister Piero Fassino said Sunday the
government's "structural strategy" would allow parliament to
calmly assess the various calls for "an act of clemency" that
would ease the pressure inside Italy's jails.
</P>
<P>
He said the over-crowded and inadequate state of the prisons
had been known for some time, adding that "the government is
working to tackle this situation both by building more jails and
by new prison regulations which will permit less pitiful and
constrained living conditions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
