<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Ready to Hold Referendum on Political System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Ding Qilin and Wang Shangzhi
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Ugandans will go to
the 17,000 polling stations across the country on June 29 in the
national referendum to determine the political system of the east
African nation.
</P>
<P>
"There are two sections of forces in Uganda, one force wants
the system of the National Resistance Movement to be continued,
and another section of people thinks the multiparty system should
be followed," Aziz Kasujja, chairman of the Ugandan National
Electoral Commission, said in an interview with Xinhua at his
office.
</P>
<P>
When the Movement took power in 1986, it promised to enable the
people of Uganda to make a constitution. In 1988 the government
set up the Uganda constitutional commission comprising of 22
eminent people.
</P>
<P>
The commission collected people's views on the new constitution
which was passed in 1995. However, on the form of governance, a
majority of Ugandans preferred the Movement (or one party) system
to continue while some people wanted a multiparty system.
</P>
<P>
The idea of holding a referendum to decide future political
system is contained in the constitution which recognizes people's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"The referendum on a political system is necessary, because the
 constitution provides for it on the basis that all power belongs
to the people," Kasujja said.
</P>
<P>
"People are given right to vote for or against either of the
systems, the Movement or the multiparty, but no one can be forced
to vote," Kasujja said.
</P>
<P>
Since the National Electoral Commission was established in
1996, it has done plenty of work to prepare for the referendum.
"Everything is ready at the final stage, and everything is going
smoothly despite of some difficulties," said the chairman.
</P>
<P>
"The major difficulty the commission has been facing is
inadequate resources," he said.
</P>
<P>
The referendum expenditure totals 22 billion Uganda shillings
(about 15 million U.S. dollars). But the commission has only
received around 13 billion shillings. Some money from donor
community has gone to the civic education in the country.
</P>
<P>
From January 17 to February, a total of 300 million shillings
was paid to the civic educators who were recruited for every
parish in the country during a civic education campaign initiated
by the Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
The education campaign countrywide has not been so successful
due to low voters' turnout, said Dick Kizito, public relations
officer of the Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
However, majority of Ugandans are expected to vote. "From scene
they demand voters' cards, we can see they are enthusiastic,"
Kasujja said.
</P>
<P>
According to a public opinion poll conducted by K2-Research
Ltd, an affiliate of K2-Consult of Denmark, 75.5 percent of the
respondents said they would vote while 23.2 percent said they
would not.
</P>
<P>
The referendum will be supervised by independent organizations.
"The commission has also invited some international observers to
supervise the exercise," said Kasujja.
</P>
<P>
"Anyhow, the referendum will be held, with security and order
being guaranteed by the government," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Zimbabwe's Parliamentary Voting Ends Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhu Shixiang
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Voting ended at 7 pm on Sunday, the
final day in Zimbabwe's two-day parliamentary election, with the
Election Directorate ruling out extension of voting and declaring
that counting begins on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
About four million of the 5.1 million registered voters were
estimated to have cast their vote by close of polling at some
4,000 polling stations in the country's 120 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Peace prevailed throughout the country during the elections in
contrast to predictions that the poll would be marred by violence.
</P>
<P>
Many people, mostly whites, fled the country with some
companies closing for fear of violence that left about 30 people
dead, 300 injured in the run up to the election since February.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Saturday when there were high turnouts everywhere,
Sunday was a mixture of long queues in some areas but none at all
in others, indicating that most people voted on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the European Union observer team Pierre Schori said his
team had not received any reports of irregularities worth talking
of.
</P>
<P>
However, there were cases of people trying to vote twice.
Police arrested some of these people, while others were simply
turned away by polling officials.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe has said the huge voter turnout and
peace showed that democracy is getting stronger in the country.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the main opposition Movement for Democratic Change
Morgan Tsvangirai said in a statement his party was happy with
the way people voted, adding that intimidation of his supporters
had receded.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 candidates from about 15 political parties and
independents are contesting 120 seats on offer in the 150-member
House of Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
