<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Oil Production Not Affected By Blast: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's oil production will
not be affected by the explosion Sunday dawn in the Mina al-Ahmadi
refinery, said Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Naser Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the statement at a press conference after he
rushed to the explosion scene for an inspection of the refinery,
which processed 440,000 barrels of crude each day.
</P>
<P>
An oil source was quoted by the official Kuwaiti News Agency as
saying that the huge blast took place Sunday morning during
attempts to control a gas leakage of a pipeline, which killed three
people and injured 43 others, and caused unspecified material
damage.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Al-Sabah told reporters that the fire caused by the
explosion has been put off, and actions and measures have been
taken to contain the situation.
</P>
<P>
The refinery has been completely closed, he said, adding it may
take several months before the factory can resume full operation.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed as "baseless and untrue" the claim that the
accident occurred because of outworn equipment, saying all the oil
installations are completely checked and repaired every two years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kuwaiti National Oil Company issued a statement,
denying the explosion might result from a sabotage operation.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the country's power plants were not affected
as fuel supply to them did not stop. Neither were the local supply
of fuel oil, liquefied gas and plane fuel, it added, thanks to the
availability of sufficient reserves.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait produces 2.37 million barrels of oil per day. Its two
other refineries of Al-Shabia and Abdullah Port, are now operating
at full capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
