<HEADLINE> Iran Burns 23 Tons of Drugs to Mark Anti-Drug Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday afternoon burned 23
tons of various seized narcotics with a market value of over 3
billion U.S. dollars to mark the international anti-drug day.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held on a hill in northern Tehran in the presence
of senior Iranian officials, foreign diplomats and representatives
of international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Under tight security, a pile of drug was set on fire, belching
heavy, black smoke into the air.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Iranian Judiciary Chief Ayatollah Hashemi
Shahroudi called on the international community, particularly the
European countries, to help Iran in its campaign against drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
"I call on all European countries and countries neighboring Iran
to expand their technological, research, training and financial
cooperation with the Islamic Republic of Iran in the global
campaign against narcotics," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shahroudi said that 2,958 Iranians sacrificed their lives in the
campaign since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Iran has spent more than 900 million dollars for the
construction of fortifications and deployment of forces in border
areas and is spending 200 million dollars more annually for the
campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that over 263 tons of various narcotics were captured in
1,445 operations.
</P>
<P>
He urged the world countries to coordinate their anti-drug
efforts, harshen punishments, and facilitate the extradition of
narcotic criminals.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed to set up a regional research and study center
on narcotics, because countries in the region are hardest hit by
the drug problem.
</P>
<P>
Iran stepped up its massive anti-drug campaigns after its Majlis
(parliament) passed a strict anti-drug law in 1989 against drug
trafficking and drug abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
