<HEADLINE> Kuwait Seizes Another Iraqi Ship for Violating U.N. Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti coast guard patrols
stopped another Iraqi ship in Kuwaiti territorial waters Saturday
night, said the Interior Ministry in a statement Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This was the second Iraqi ship seized in 24 hours. According to
the statement carried by the official Kuwaiti News Agency, the ship
was one its way from Iraq's southern port of Umm Qasr to the United
Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
It said the ship, with an eight-member crew on board, was
carrying 449 heads of sheep. The previous ship intercepted Saturday
morning was an oil tanker, carrying 650 tons of diesel oil.
</P>
<P>
There have been four Iraqi ships stopped by the Kuwaiti coast
guard patrols in Kuwaiti territorial waters between May and June,
for violating the U.N. economic sanctions imposed after Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The ships were found to be carrying leatherware, wool, lentil,
dates and grain, the Kuwaiti statement said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under 10-year-old crippling U.N. sanctions, which
had banned Iraq from conducting practically all trade until limited
oil sales were permitted in 1996 under the U.N. oil-for-food
program for Iraq to buy humanitarian supplies for its people.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food program was expanded last December to allow
virtually free oil sales, but still under U.N. supervision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
