<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Defense Minister Clarifies Armament Policy as Self-Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Second Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister of Defense Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz said his
country's armament policy aims at achieving self-sufficiency and
protecting the public security and sanctities.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference with visiting French Defense
Minister Alain Richard in Saudi Red Sea port city of Jeddah late
Saturday night, Prince Sultan said Saudi Kingdom was not confined
its arms imports to any specific country.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has worked out five-year and ten-year plans and the
strategies for maintaining its security and serving the Arab Nation
especially the member countries of the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) and the Damascus Declaration, Prince Sultan added.
</P>
<P>
On the Saudi-French accord for the supply of French Le Claire
tanks and ground defense systems, he said the Kingdom has been
studying the supply of such tanks and systems since three years
ago. Seven Saudi army officers have been cooperating with their
French counterparts in the development of the tanks since then.
</P>
<P>
France is one of the earliest countries that cooperate with
Saudi Arabia sincerely and positively, the Saudi official noted,
adding that the cooperation is growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
In the light of balanced economic cooperation between Saudi
Arabia and France, the Kingdom seeks to develop joint ventures to
serve the interests of both countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are joint Saudi-French committees that work hard to
determine whether the supply of Le Claire tanks would be in the
form of purchase or manufacturing and the possibility of private
sector involvement in the deal, the Saudi minister added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Richard said he discussed with Prince Sultan the
Middle East peace process, noting that France was trying to find an
solution acceptable to all concerned parties in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the Syrian-Israeli peace track, he said France holds that the
basis for peace should be the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
As for the joint military manufacturing, Richard said France
wants to establish a strategic partnership with Saudi Arabia and
enhance the military cooperation to serve the world peace, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz received the French defense
minister upon the latter's arrival in Jeddah Saturday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
