<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Conservative Judiciary Closes Another Reformist Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary on
Sunday closed the daily Bayan, one of the few reformist newspapers
left after the mass closure of 17 reformist papers and journals by
conservative courts in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The clerical court ordered to suspend the publication of the
daily, citing offenses of the Constitution, the Islamic penal code
as well as the press law as reasons, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The managing editor of Bayan is Ali Akbar Mohtashamipur, an
adviser to reform-minded President Mohammad Khatami and a former
interior minister.
</P>
<P>
As a medium-ranking cleric, Mohtashamipur was reportedly
summoned by the special court recently. The clerical court is
responsible for handling offenses committed by religious figures.
</P>
<P>
Iran's conservative courts ordered the closure of the 17
reformist
publications in the past few months as a way to crack down on the
country's growing reformist campaign which pushed reformers to the
landslide victory of parliamentary elections in February.
</P>
<P>
Tehran's Justice Department announced Sunday that the court
hearings for the banned publications will begin next Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
