<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Jews Charged With Spying May Face Death Penalty: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Public prosecutor Ayatollah
Morteza Moqtadae said Sunday that the 13 Iranian Jews charged with
spying for Israel could be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
Moqtadae's remarks were contradictory to those made by another
judiciary official who assured earlier that the accused would not
face death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Moqtadae said the Jews have been found guilty of spying for "the
Zionist regime" (Israel), and according to law they could be
sentenced to either death or prison terms, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, the official further noted that
the legal proceedings against the suspects did not indicate that
they would not be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the head of justice in Iran's southern Fars
Province, Hossein Ali Amiri, dismissed speculations that the Jews
would be sentenced to death, saying they are not charged with "
mohareb" (waging war against God and the country), the only crime
carrying the death penalty in the case.
</P>
<P>
Court hearings for the accused Jews began on April 13 in Shiraz,
capital of Fars Province, and formally concluded on Saturday. So
far at least eight of the suspects have reportedly confessed to
passing on classified information to Israel and having connections
with Israel's security service.
</P>
<P>
Amiri said the court ruling on the suspects would be issued
within a week following the conclusion of the hearings. The verdict
will
also concern four Muslims charged with the same offenses.
</P>
<P>
Under the Western powers' pressure to release the Jews, Iran
insists that the arrests of them, in March 1999, had nothing to do
with their religious backgrounds and no foreign country should
interfere in Iran's internal affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
