<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Legislators Sentenced to Jail Terms for Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Higher State Security Court
on Sunday sentenced three members of the People's Assembly
(Parliament) from the ruling National Democratic Party to 10 years
in jail for their role in misuse of public money.
</P>
<P>
Another parliament member, Ibrahim Aglane, was given a one-year
suspended sentence for his part in the country's biggest corruption
scandal in 20 years, involving 32 defendants in fraudulently
obtaining around 470 million U.S. dollars in loans, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Aglane received a lighter punishment than the other MPs because
he had repaid the money he fraudulently received, the news agency
said, without mentioning the sum.
</P>
<P>
The four MPs, Tawfiq Abdu Ismail, Khaled Mahmud, Mahmud Azzam
and Aglane, were present at the court amid tight security measures
at the session ending a three-year trial.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced 28 bankers and businessmen to prison terms
ranging between one year and 15 years in jail with hard labor. The
verdicts can not be appealed.
</P>
<P>
The scandal was revealed in early 1995 when President of the
Nile Bank Issa al-Ayouti accused his daughter Aleya of
misappropriation of funds.
</P>
<P>
Aleya was sentenced to 15 years in absentia after failing to
return from France, where she was allowed to go last year by a
special court authorization giving her a two-week leave from Egypt.
Issa al-Ayouti himself was also found guilty in the case and was
sentenced to 10 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
Five banks -- the commercial Dakahlia Bank, the Bank of Suez
Canal, the Nile Bank, Al-Mohandess Bank and Faisal Islamic Bank --
have been damaged in the case since the defendants
failed to return millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to investigations, a broad section of the business
community, from import-export firms to real estate, got involved in
the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
