<HEADLINE> Allied Forces to Remain in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of Zimbabwe and Namibia
said Sunday they will only withdraw their troops from the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) when peace and stability is
restored in the country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe and Namibian President Sam
Nujoma made the remarks after they held a three-hour meeting here
with DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process would dictate when the withdrawal should
start. We will remain until we are guaranteed of peace and
security in the Congo," Mugabe told reporters after the summit.
</P>
<P>
"The withdrawal from the DRC will only be when peace and
stability is restored and when a democratic process of election in
a peaceful environment is guaranteed," Nujoma said.
</P>
<P>
Asked when the elections would be held in the DRC, Kabila said
the elections would be held when the invading countries Rwanda and
Uganda withdraw from his country.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said he had already asked the Organization of African
Unity to choose another facilitator to replace former Botswana
President Ketumile Masire.
</P>
<P>
In March Masire stormed out of the Congo saying Kabila's
government had prevented him from carrying out his duties.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed the withdrawal of Rwandan and Ugandan
troops from the northern Congolese city of Kisangani where the two
former allies repeatedly clashed.
</P>
<P>
Kabila briefed the two heads of state on the situation in the
DRC.
</P>
<P>
The allied forces from Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola have been
in the DRC since the conflict started in August 1998 to help
Kabila's forces fight rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda trying to
topple his government.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos could not attend the
summit because of political problems in his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
