<HEADLINE> Mozambique Declares War Against Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The greatest challenge facing
Mozambicans is the struggle against absolute poverty, President
Joaquim Chissano declared here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the capital's Independence Square to celebrate the
25th anniversary of Mozambican independence in 1975, Chissano said
the battle to overcome poverty "requires renewed effort,
commitment and determination, and a collective belief in success".
</P>
<P>
"It is fundamental that all of society should participate in
developing a programme that seeks to concentrate efforts on
improving the living conditions of Mozambican families,
particularly rural house holds," he added.
</P>
<P>
He called for a faster rate of growth in the countryside, while
 simultaneously improving basic social services such as health
care, education and the supply of clean drinking water.
</P>
<P>
"Some courageous measures of structural adjustment taken by the
 government, such as the privatization, did not only bring the
positive results expected, but also some social problems,
particularly in the area of employment," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Absolute poverty persists, particularly in the countryside,
and regional imbalances are sharpening," Chissano said.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also called for a vigorous fight against corruption,
which he described as "an insidious and destructive evil which,
by diverting resources for individual profit, causes development
programmes to atrophy".
</P>
<P>
Chissano urged that special attention be paid to AIDS "which is
 spreading alarmingly, with a negative impact on economic
development programmes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
