<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Sunday
Israel is still open to peace talks with Syria, but its policy on
the sovereignty of the northeast bank of Lake Kinneret is not
changed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Sunday morning's weekly cabinet meeting, Barak
reiterated the extent of Israeli withdrawal from the strategic
Golan Heights, which Israel occupied during the 1967 Middle East
War, depends on security arrangement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, he added, the northeast shore of Lake Kinneret will
remain under Israeli control, according to a statement issued by
Barak's office after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Barak was responding to his Justice Minister Yossi Beilin's
early remarks on the Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, one of the prime minister's closest aides, indicated on
Saturday night that the government might agree to give Damascus
some access to the Kinneret in order to renew talks with Syria. (
Israel-Syria-Kinneret)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union observers monitoring the
Zimbabwean parliamentary elections said on Sunday that the first
day of polling was generally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Schori, a Swedish national, said that it was peaceful
except for a few exceptions of intimidation and violence, reports
reaching here quoted the chief EU observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Voting resumed on Sunday for the second and final day and polls
were due to close in the early evening local time. The final
result for the 120 contested parliamentary seats is expected to be
made known on Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 5 million people are eligible to cast their ballots in the
Zimbabwean poll, the most significant one since the country's
independence 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The poll follows four months of state-supported holdings of
white-owned farms by veterans of the country's liberation war that
won it independence from Rhodesia in 1980. (EU-Zimbabwe-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Sunday noted that
the coming weeks would be decisive and serious as the Palestinian
statehood would be declared by the end of them, said a report
reaching here from the West Bank City of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who made a speech at the Kamal Gunblat School
playground in Nablus, said, "Decisive and the most serious weeks
are ahead of us, because the independent Palestinian state will be
declared by the end of them."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiating teams set September 13 for
reaching a final agreement on the future of Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
So far, the open and secret rounds of talks between Israel and
the Palestinians failed to iron out such a deal as there was a
wide gap in standings of both sides over such thorny issues as
Jerusalem, refugees, settlements, prisoners, water and borders.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, Israeli army officers threatened to take
military actions against the Palestinian territories, which
infused tension into the Palestinian-Israeli relations. (
Palestine-Arafat-Coming Weeks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Malaysian hostage released by the Muslim
extremist group Abu Sayyaf expressed here Sunday his gratitude for
his release and hoped for an early release of other hostages still
held captive by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to thank Allah...and...to release me and I hope as
soon as possible my friends, the other hostages, will be released
as soon as possible," Zulkurnain Bin Hashim, 29, said at a press
brief held in the Presidential Palace here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado disclosed at the
briefing that Hashim's release was actually secured last Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
Hashim was quietly brought to the southern city of Zamboanga
Friday and turned over to him Saturday, he added.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado reiterated that no ransom was paid and no political
promise was made in the release of Hashim, which he said was a "
goodwill gesture" of the Abu Sayyaf.(Philippine-Hostage) 
</P>
</TEXT>
