<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Improving Awareness of Brand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Until recently, most traditional
Chinese farmers didn't make the connection between savvy marketing
strategies and rice and vegetables with catchy names.
</P>
<P>
Farmer-entrepreneuer Gong Xuebin, president of the Longda Group
and maker of Longda-brand vegetables, was one of the first to
realize that customers will return to a name they trust.
</P>
<P>
"We are engaged in China's agricultural industrialization, and
we are trying to set up a worldwide agricultural brand," said the
50-year-old Gong.
</P>
<P>
His heat-cured meat has gained a good reputation over the past
five years, and the Longda vegetables sell well in supermarkets in
Japan, the United States, and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
NHK, Japan's premier TV station, wants to interview Gong at
Longda headquarters in east China's Shandong province.
</P>
<P>
Longda is currently among the top 500 village and township
enterprises in China, with 10 joint ventures and total assets of
810 million yuan, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
More and more modern Chinese farmers like Gong have deepened
their marketing know-how, introducing useful business strategies
into the sales of agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Xinlong county in north China's Hebei province, for instance,
is famed for growing Chinese chestnuts. Over the past few years,
the county has promoted several high-quality brands of chestnut,
which have been welcomed in Japan and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
"Baotashan" apples, produced in northwest China's Shaanxi
province, are also well-sold in European markets.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in east China's Zhejiang Province have registered
nearly 40 brands of rice, which have provided more options for
local consumers.
</P>
<P>
Marketing experts here say that more famous agricultural brands
will emerge as Chinese farmers gain a greater understanding of
marketing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
