<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freed Malaysian hostage Hopes Early Release of Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian hostage released by
the Muslim extremist group Abu Sayyaf expressed here Sunday his
gratitude for his release and hoped for an early release of other
hostages still held captive by the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to thank Allah...and...to release me ad I hope as
soon as possible my friends, the other hostages, will be released
as soon as possible." Zulkurnain Bin Hashim, 29, said at a press
brief held in the Presidential Palace here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado disclosed at the
briefing that Hashim's release was actually secured last Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
Hashim was quietly brought to the southern city of Zamboanga
Friday and turned over to him Saturday, he added.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado reiterated that no ransom was paid and no political
promise was made in the release of Hashim, which he said was a "
goodwill gesture" of the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
when Hashim was asked how the hostages were treated, Aventajado
said Hashim assured him that the hostages were treated well. "He
is very much in good shape as you can see," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hashim's release is the biggest break so far in the two-month-
long hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf group is still holding captive three Germans,
two French, two Finns, two South Africans, one Lebanese, eight
other Malaysians and two Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were kidnapped by Abu Sayyaf rebels on April 23
from the diving resort of Sipadan in neighboring Malaysia and
taken to Jolo island in the southern Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
