<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coming Weeks "Decisive" for Palestinian Statehood: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on
Sunday noted that the coming weeks would be decisive and serious as
the Palestinian statehood would be declared by the end of them,
said a report reaching here from the West Bank City of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who made a speech at the Kamal Gunblat School playground
in Nablus, said,"Decisive and the most serious weeks are ahead of
us, because the independent Palestinian state will be declared by
the end of them."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiating teams set September 13 for
reaching a final agreement on the future of Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
So far, the open and secret rounds of talks between Israel and
the Palestinians failed to iron out such a deal as there was a wide
gap in standings of both sides over such thorny issues as
Jerusalem, refugees, settlements, prisoners, water and borders.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, Israeli army officers threatened to take
military actions against the Palestinian territories, which infused
tension into the Palestinian-Israeli relations.
</P>
<P>
In response, Arafat said,"No one should threaten us. We are for
peace, the just and comprehensive peace. We are proud of our sons,
friends and allies in South Lebanon, Egypt, Jordan and Syria." 
</P>
<P>
The problem of Palestinian independence has been a controversial
and sensitive topic since the peace process between Israel and the
Palestinians was launched. 
</P>
<P>
Such a "Palestinian entity", according to Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, should be established on the West Bank territories
evacuated by the Israel Defense Forces. 
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinian side has been insisting that according
to the Oslo accords, an independent Palestinian state should be
established on all of the West Bank with east Jerusalem as its
capital. 
</P>
<P>
So far, the Palestinians have full or partial control of about
40 percent of the West Bank territories. Arafat reiterated several
times that an independent Palestinian state will be established no
later than September 13, 2000, the day set for the two sides to
sign a final accord for permanent status issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
