<HEADLINE> Cut My Hand If I Steal, Says Nigeria Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Zamfara State Governor,
Alhaji Sani, has challenged those accusing him of fraud and
insincerity in the implementation of the Islamic law Sharia to
produce evidence, reported Nigerian press on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He reportedly said that he was ready to face an Sharia court
and if found guilty, let his right hand be cut-off.
</P>
<P>
Sani is the first governor in the Africa's most populous
country, to introduce the controversy Islamic law Sharia in
January of this year into a state, which followed nationwide
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
The riot over the proposed implementation of Sharia in the
country's northern Kaduna State in February of this year killed
about 1,000 people. Sani made the statement on Saturday in
Kaduna, capital of Nigeria's Kaduna State, amidst allegations by
officials of the country's ruling Peoples Democratic Party (PDP)
that he is not transparent and sincere in the execution of most
projects, the costs of which they alleged were highly inflated.
</P>
<P>
"What I want my detractors to say is that me as a governor who
 introduced Sharia has been alleged to have either taken money
from contractors or siphoned money from government account," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Let them dare say it. You will hear the first case of Alkali
court with the governor and if I am found guilty my hand should
be amputated," said the governor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
