<HEADLINE> Blair Puts Labor Lawmakers on Election Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has placed Labor lawmakers on alert for a possible snap general
election this autumn, according to a Sunday Express report on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted party insiders as saying last week that Blair
put Labor's Members of Parliament (MPs) on a war footing when he
addressed them at a private meeting.
</P>
<P>
They said the possibility of an autumn poll is why he withdrew
his spokesman Alastair Campbell from the front line and gave him a
strategic planning role.
</P>
<P>
However, Sunday Express said, May 2001 remains the likeliest
date for the next election and is favored by Blair's top pollster,
Philip Gould.
</P>
<P>
An election this autumn would be only three-and-a-half years
since the May 1, 1997 general election and would be a huge gamble
by Labor, it added.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest problem would be explaining why a Govenment with a
majority of 180 needs to hold an election so soon," admitted one
party official.
</P>
<P>
The Opposition Saturday accused Blair of planning to "cut and
run," but insisted they were ready for a snap autumn poll if it
happened. "It all adds up," said shadow cabinet member Andrew
Lansley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
