<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Polls Generally Peaceful: EU Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union observers
monitoring the Zimbabwean parliamentary elections said on Sunday
that the first day of polling was generally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Schori, a Swedish national, said that it was peaceful
except for a few exceptions of intimidation and violence, reports
reaching here quoted the chief EU observer as saying.
</P>
<P>
Voting resumed on Sunday for the second and final day and polls
were due to close in the early evening local time. The final
result for the 120 contested parliamentary seats is expected to be
made known on Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 5 million people are eligible to cast their ballots in the
Zimbabwean poll, the most significant one since the country's
independence 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The poll follows four months of state-supported holdings of
white-owned farms by veterans of the country's liberation war that
won it independence from Rhodesia in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has been monitoring the preparation and
process of the Zimbabwean parliamentary elections and has
stationed 150 observers in the southern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
