<HEADLINE> China's Pillar Industries in Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial companies saw a
profit of 12.54 million yuan (about 1.5 million U.S. dollars) in
the first five months of the year, 1.3 times more in a comparison
with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Steel output in the first five months was 50,750 tons, up 3.48
percentage points; profits in the textile industry reached 7.99
billion yuan, a 3.4 percent rise; the coal industry reduced losses
by 230 million yuan in the last five months; and the sugar
industry reduced losses of 230 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The petrochemical industry realized profits of 31 billion yuan,
the same amount as last year. The aim of profits for the industry
is 60 billion yuan for the entire year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, China has closed 36,000 small coal mines, ordered 5,
600 oil refineries with outdated machinery to stop production, and
shut down 111 small oil refineries with low-quality production,
serious pollution and managing problems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Shi Wanpeng, deputy minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, said the growth was due to the national efforts to
rein in rampant smuggling, which has inspired exports and
intensified reforms in State-owned companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Meteorological Satellite EDS-Details added </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XICHANG, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China successfully launched a
meteorological satellite here at 19:50 (Beijing time) today.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, called the Fengyun 2, was launched by a Long
March 3 carrier rocket at the Xichang Satellite Launch Center in
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the second geostationary meteorological satellite China
has launched. It is an improved version of the first Fengyun 2
meteorological satellite launched by China in 1997, Chinese
experts said. The satellite has a designed life span of three
years.
</P>
<P>
The rocket measuring 44.9 meters in length has a boosting
capacity of 300 tons. It is designed by Chinese scientists. This
is the 13th time that a Long March 3 carrier rocket was blasted
off and the 61st launch of a Long March rocket series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
