<HEADLINE> Meretz to Have Role From Outside Government: Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel's left-wing Meretz Party
leader Yossi Sarid said on Sunday that his party's role in matters
of government policy would become apparent within the next few
days, Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
Sarid, a staunch supporter of the peace process with the
Palestinians, said he had not been invited to any meetings with
Prime Minister Ehud Barak after the coalition crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meretz ministers resigned from the coalition last week in a move
that helped Barak end the crisis with Shas party, while pledging
continued support to the government from the outside.
</P>
<P>
Sarid expressed his hope that the resignation be only temporary,
and said if he returns to the government, he will return only to
the Education Ministry, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Meretz's long-running dispute with the ultra-Orthodox's Shas
party over funding for the latter's school system led to a grave
coalition crisis in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Meretz finally made the concession to quit the coalition so as
to enable Prime Minister Ehud Barak to keep Shas within the
coalition. Shas is the third largest party with 17 seats in the
Knesset (parliament) and the largest ruling partner of Barak's One
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The real intention, said Meretz, was to support Barak's efforts
on the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks which have entered a
critical stage with the September deadline for a permanent final-
status accord looming.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, a fresh crisis has emerged to threaten Barak's
coalition as Interior Minister Natan Sharansky warned of his
possible resignation over reported concessions being made to the
Palestinians in peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Washington for a summit on Sunday, Sharansky
called for the formation of a national unity government which is to
draft a common platform by all on the peace negotiations with the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
