<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Failure Occurs Frequently in Ethiopian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Residents, particularly
businessmen, in Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa have been
complaining power rationing which was reportedly hurting varieties
of business in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Electric and Power Corporation (EEPC) is turning
the lights off without a weekly schedule, Alemayehu Seyoum,
administrator of a medical center, told local mass media.
</P>
<P>
"Even if we use the timetable properly, the irony is, we do not
know when and where the power blackout is going to strike next,"
he said, noting the power outrages might have done damages to
vital sectors of the center at any time.
</P>
<P>
Some bar owners said that in the past few weeks they had been
forced to carry their draft beer canisters to neighborhoods where
there is power to chill the beer. Otherwise, they say, the beer
would be undrinkable and they would lose money.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some private newspaper publishers have been forced
to move office equipment frequently to areas with power supply to
ensure that readers get their copies in time.
</P>
<P>
For two successive weekends, many sports lovers did not have
pleasure of watching the on-going Euro 2000 Football Competition
because of power failure.
</P>
<P>
Power rationing has been a popular way in Ethiopia to overcome
the shortage of power in the country where hydroelectricity has
been the sole public power resource. The practice of power
rationing is very much common in the capital in the dry season.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, the frequency of power failure in Addis
Ababa has been speeded up from once every four days to once every
other day. The power failure normally lasts 15 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
According to EEPC officials, the frequent power failure in the
capital is due to the shortage of water in the dams to run the
turbines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
