<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharansky Threatens To Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A fresh crisis is threatening
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition government after
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky warned he may resign over
reported concessions being made to the Palestinians in the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharansky voiced his opposition to the holding of a
three-way summit between Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and U.S. President Bill Clinton in the near future, urging Barak to
form a national unity government before the summit and before
reaching a framework agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The government, in its current configuration, has reached the
end of its road," Sharansky told the Army Radio on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"A national unity government should draft a common platform
agreed upon by all," Sharansky said, adding that "if this did not
happen, Israel would soon have to back down from its principles."
</P>
<P>
He also complained that coalition members have no information
regarding current negotiations and what he was hearing from
unofficial sources has worried him.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky sent a letter to Barak on Friday, accusing Barak of
preparing a complex strategy aimed at ratifying the framework
agreement between Israel and the Palestinians at the expense of his
coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Sharansky outlined Barak's concessions that he is
ready to give to the Palestinians, which he said he will not
support them.
</P>
<P>
The concessions include giving up Israel's control in certain
parts of Jerusalem, the right of return for the Palestinian
refugees to the June 4, 1967 lines, and having the Jordan River,
its bridges, and the Jordan Valley transferred to Palestinian
sovereignty, according to Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Prime Minister's Office said Barak has sent a
letter to Sharansky responding that "not agreement has been
reached with the Palestinian at this stage."
</P>
<P>
Barak said that Sharansky's information is inaccurate and "do
not correctly describe the Israeli position at the present time"
and that he supports the formation of a broader coalition based on
the guidelines that he promised to his voters before last year's
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
