<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Approves Shahak's Transportation Portfolio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Cabinet approved
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's nomination of Center Party leader Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak as Transportation Minister on Sunday, leaving his
post of Minister of Tourism vacant.
</P>
<P>
The former chief of staff also automatically becomes a permanent
member of the prime minister's security cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Lipkin-Shahak is replacing Yitzhak Mordechai who resigned
following an indictment on sexual assault charges against him.
Lipkin-Shahak took over Mordechai's position as head of the Center
Party a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Barak intended to name Center Party's No. 2 man Dan Meridor,
chairman of the Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee of the
Knesset (parliament), to succeed Lipkin-Shahak as Tourism Minister.
But Meridor has refrained from accepting the offer.
</P>
<P>
Meridor was reported to have set his sights on other posts such
as the Justice Ministry portfolio now held by Yossi Beilin (One
Israel) in light of Barak's intention to reshuffle the government
by using the opportunity of Mordechai's resignation.
</P>
<P>
Meridor was also said to be interested in receiving the Defense
portfolio, now held by Barak.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, a retired general at age 55, resigned as
transportation minister at the end of May in the face of charges
that he sexually assaulted three women over the past eight years.
If convicted, he can face up to seven years in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
