<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Increasing Industrial Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial sector
maintained a steady growth in the first four months this year,
according to figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The added value of industry increased by 10.9 percent on an
annual basis to reach 694.1 billion yuan (about 83.8 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The added value of light industry in the four months stood at
286.8 billion yuan, up 9.9 percent year on year, and that of heavy
industry at 407.3 billion yuan, surging 12.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
An added value of 416.2 billion yuan came from the state-owned
and state-holding enterprises, up 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, collectively-owned enterprises, a component of
the public economy, reported an added value of 97.0 billion yuan,
up 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The added value of enterprises with foreign investment and
investment from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan amounted to 151.2
billion yuan, a year-on-year growth of 14.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The statistics covered all enterprises in the state and non-
state sectors with the annual product sales revenue at and above
five million yuan each.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
