<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Timber Output Continues to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China's output of timber plunged
13.8 percent year on year in the first four months of this year to
9.83 million cubic meters, according to the National Bureau of
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Production of saw wood also witnessed a decline of 5.1 percent
on an annual basis, amounting to 679,300 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has imposed a ban on irrational
lumbering in many forest areas, particularly those on the upper
reaches of major rivers in a bid to curb soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Many experts have blamed the excessive logging of trees in the
past as one of the major reasons for the devastating flooding in
southern and northeastern China in the summer of 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Report on Air Quality in 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese cities enjoyed good air
quality today, according to the China Environmental Monitoring
Center.
</P>
<P>
The center reported fairly good air in 30 cities -- Beijing,
Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Hohhot, Shenyang, Dalian,
Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Hefei, Fuzhou, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan,
Changsha, Zhanjiang, Chongqing, Chengdu, Guiyang, Xi'an, Xining
and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
All the 30 aforementioned cities listed particulates less than
10 microns in size as their major pollutants, with their air
pollution indexes no higher than 100.
</P>
<P>
It also reported excellent air in 12 cities -- Xiamen, Nanchang,
Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou, Nanning, Haikou, Kunming,
Lanzhou, Lhasa and Yinchuan, with their air pollution indexes no
higher than 50.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing and Guiyang reported sulfur dioxide as their major
air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes at or below
50), level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 51
to 100), level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes
ranging from 101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes
ranging from 201 to 300), and level-five or hazardous (pollution
indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
