<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Reformist Party Urges Amendment to Election Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A major reformist party in Iran on
Sunday urged the new Majlis (parliament) to amend the election law
so that the nation's election process can be protected.
</P>
<P>
The sixth Majlis election in February showed that as long as
relevant authorities do not conform with their responsibility and
the power is accumulated in an irresponsible hand, there is no hope
of protecting the nation's election, the Islamic Iran Participation
Front (IIPF) said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The influential party, led by President Mohammad Khatami's
younger brother Mohammad Reza Khatami who is currently vice speaker
of the Majlis, was actually criticizing the conservative Guardians
Council (GC).
</P>
<P>
As the powerful supervisor of the February election, the GC has
so far annulled first-round and runoff election results in some 10
constituencies, voiding as many as two million votes. It has also
rejected the victory of a number of reformist candidates, awarding
their seats to their conservative rivals.
</P>
<P>
The measures, however, failed to stop the reformists from
seizing absolute control of the new Majlis from the conservative
establishment.
</P>
<P>
The new parliament started work on May 27, with 276 of the total
290 seats filled. The IIPF and other reformist parties have
occupied 80 percent of the filled seats.
</P>
<P>
The statement, quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency, also
urged the people to remain calm and patient in the face of the
conservative pressure so that one day they can show their "strong
will and determination" again.
</P>
<P>
All the people, especially those in constituencies where the
polls were nullified, should go their way for materialization of
the reform movement, it added.
</P>
<P>
Iran's reformist campaign has been growing since moderate
President Khatami won a landslide victory in the presidential
election in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Reformers in the new Majlis have vowed to reverse legislation
passed by the conservative fifth Majlis to hinder President
Khatami's social and cultural reform programs.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the new Majlis passed an urgent motion to
review the press law, which was amended by its predecessor in the
last days of its term to impose more restrictions on the reformist
press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
