<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voter Turnout in Japan's Lower House Race Lower Due to Bad Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Japanese voters went to cast their
ballots for the House of Representatives general election Sunday,
but early voter turnout was lower than expected because of bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
As of 4 p.m. (local time), an estimated 41.44 percent of
eligible voters across Japan cast ballots, 5.37 percentage points
lower than the figure for the corresponding time in the previous
lower house election in 1996, when the final turnout hit a record-
low 59.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
When balloting started at 7 a.m. (local time), rainy or cloudy
weather prevailed throughout Japan except Hokkaido, Japan's
northernmost main island.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,404 candidates are vying for 480 seats, 300 in
single-seat constituencies and the remaining 180 in the
proportional-representation section. The number of lower house
seats up for grabs was cut by 20 from 500 as a result of electoral
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The total number of eligible voters is 107 million, a record
high.
</P>
<P>
One focal point of the election is whether the ruling coalition,
comprising of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), New Komeito and
New Conservative Party, can win 254 seats to secure a stable
majority in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Attention is also focused on how many seats the LDP alone can
gain. LDP Secretary General Hiromu Nonaka has set the goal at 229
seats.
</P>
<P>
The targets are well below the number of seats the tripartite
coalition controlled prior to the dissolution of the lower chamber
on June 2. At that time, the coalition held 336 seats, 271 of
which were held by the LDP.
</P>
<P>
Recent opinion polls conducted by Japan's leading newspapers,
however, showed that the coalition was on its way to securing a
stable majority, although a high percentage of undecided voters,
between 30 percent and 50 percent, made the results difficult to
predict.
</P>
<P>
In the election campaign, the ruling coalition said it will
continue economic efforts aimed at putting Japan's economy, which
posted plus growth in fiscal 1999 after two years of contraction,
firmly on a path toward sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, meanwhile, criticized the ruling bloc for
trying to spend its way out of the recession, and called for
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The opposition bloc also blamed a series of controversial
remarks made by Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori, including one in
which he said Japan is "a divine nation with the emperor at its
center." Critics said the remark echoed the ideology that drove
Japan's wartime militarism.
</P>
<P>
The LDP registered 337 candidates for the race, while the New
Komeito fielded 74, and the New Conservative Party 19.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ) fielded 262,
while the Japanese Communist Party (JCP) entered 332, among others.
The results for most of the seats are expected to be known early
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Minister of Construction and Housing
Yitzhak Levy and his American counterpart Andrew Cuomo have signed
a memorandum of understanding establishing a Binational Commission
on Housing and Community Development.
</P>
<P>
The new commission will promote cooperative efforts in
integrating advanced building technologies and encourage joint
ventures between Israeli and American construction firms.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two weeks after a general strike was averted by
freezing preparations to implement the Ben-Bassat income tax reform
plan, the Israeli Finance Ministry and Histadrut labor federation
are no closer to reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
One June 11, one day prior to the scheduled strike, Finance
Minister Avraham Shochat announced a three-week freeze on plans to
implement disputed sections of the tax reform package and said the
three-week period would be used to arrive at consensus with labor
leaders.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Economic officials in Jerusalem expect Bank of
Israel Governor David Klein to announce on Monday the nominal
interest rate will remain unchanged for another month at 9.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
If this assessment is correct, it will mark the second month in
a row that interest rates remain unchanged, following six straight
months of interest rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
Klein believes the rate of interests is now in line with the
government's inflation target of 3 to 4 percent from the years 2000
and 2001.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman is to raise the ceiling on foreign equity
participation in the services sector from 49 percent to 70 percent
early next year, according to Sunday's Dubai based daily "Gulf
News".
</P>
<P>
In addition, a company with foreign equity of up to 70 percent
will be treated the same as a wholly-owned Omani company in terms
of taxation, the paper quoted the economic expert at the
Sultanate's Ministry of Commerce and Industries as saying.
</P>
<P>
This is going to be a major step forward, for which new
legislations will be enacted," Dr. Said Al-Riyami said in an
interview to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
