<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Call for Israeli Troop Withdrawal from West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Sunday stressed the need for
Israel to carry out the third phase of troop withdrawal from the
West Bank, the Egyptian information minister said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Arafat termed as "important" for Israel to go ahead
with the pullout, which was to have taken place on Friday, Safwat
el-Sherif told reporters after a meeting between the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Israel has put off the troop withdrawal till July 7 as agreed by
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"There are still obstacles and tough issues of contention
between the negotiating delegations," said el-Sherif, who attended
the talks in a presidential palace in northern Cairo.
</P>
<P>
But efforts are being made by all the concerned parties in a bid
to overcome the differences, he added.
</P>
<P>
Little progress has been made in the Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations for a final peace agreement, planned for September 13,
on the thorniest issues, including the border of a future
Palestinian state, the status of Jerusalem and Jewish settlements,
and the fate of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been trying to bring together Arafat,
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.S. President Bill Clinton
to seek a breakthrough in the peace talks. But Palestinian
officials have ruled out imminent convocation, saying that Arafat
will go to such a summit only for the signing of a peace accord
other than negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here Saturday evening and ended the visit after
the talks with Mubarak. He frequently travels to Cairo for
consultations on the peace process. 
</P>
