<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 210 Million Dollars WB Aid to Bangladesh Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The fate of the 210 million U.S.
dollars assistance from the World Bank (WB) has become uncertain,
due to the failure of the government to submit a fresh program to
it for rehabilitation of the country's ailing jute industry, the
Financial Express reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted sources as saying that after discontinuation
of its Jute Sector Adjustment Credit (JSAC), the WB asked the
government of Bangladesh in August, 1997 to come up with a fresh
program about the modalities for privatizing the mills in the
government sector and the ways for making them commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
A special committee of the government prepared an outline of a
Revised Jute Sector Rehabilitation Program and submitted it to the
Jute Ministry on November, 1997. But the ministry had failed to
submit it to the WB.
</P>
<P>
The WB under its JSAC program disbursed a total of 40 million
dollars as financial assistance to the jute industry here out of
total allocation of 250 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The WB has discontinued the assistance since 1996 as the
program seemed to be ineffective. The bank claimed that it would
not disburse the remaining fund until the government is determined
to transfer the public sector to private hands.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Jute's slowness over the recommendation only
retards the privatization process of the public sector mills, the
sources said, adding that if the government can submit a fresh
proposal, there is a possibility for the country's jute sector to
get the remaining 210 million dollars from the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
