<HEADLINE> Frozen Foods Stranded at Bangladeshi Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Frozen foods worth about 40 million
U.S.dollars remained stranded at the Mongla port, 200 kilometers
southwest of Dhaka, due to lack of ocean going vessels, sources in
the sea port disclosed to Xinhua Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Almost a similar quantity of sea foods are also struck up at a
number of plants in and around Khulna, about 350 kilometers
southwest of the capital, the hub of Bangladesh's sea food
industry, as factory owners could not process their products due
to lack of containers.
</P>
<P>
At least two vessels were scheduled to ship the sea foods from
Mongla, but none of them reached the port till Saturday. The ships
have remained stranded at the outer anchorage of Chittagong Port,
200 kilometers southeast of Dhaka since June 17 due to berthing
problems.
</P>
<P>
Unless arrangements are made immediately for the arrival of the
ships at Mongla port by June 26-27, most of the Letter of Credits
will be expired, the sources said, and exporters and entrepreneurs
will have to face a tough monetary situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 50 frozen foods exporters of the Khulna region
in a joint statement Saturday sought intervention from the prime
minister for immediate arrangement of vessel to ship the
exportable shrimp.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the shortage of vessels at Mongla Port, exporters
said huge quantity of shrimp remains piled at the plants when the
season of export gets momentum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Million People Suffer from Diabetes in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The number of diabetic patients
in Pakistan is rising at an alarming rate and has now reached the
15 million mark.
</P>
<P>
At present 8 to 10 percent of the diabetics patients are in
Karachi and 12 percent each in Lahore and in the twin cities of
Rawalpindi and Islamabad, the Associated Press of Pakistan
reported by quoting the Pakistan Diabetic Association.
</P>
<P>
Further more, the number of male diabetic patients is one
percent higher than the female patients in the country.
</P>
<P>
There are two main types of diabetes. In Type I diabetes the
pancreas fails to produce insulin which is essential for survival.
In this cas, insulin must be administered by injection.
</P>
<P>
Type I is more common in children and adolescents and accounts
for 10 to 15 percent of all diabetes.
</P>
<P>
Type II diabetes occurs when the body is unable to produce
enough insulin to meet body requirements or when it cannot
properly use the produced insulin.
</P>
<P>
This condition can be controlled through diet, oral medication
and routine exercise. Type II occurs primarily in adults and is by
far the most common form of diabetes, accounting for 85 and 90
percent of all diabetes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspects in General Santos City Bombings Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Authorities said Sunday they have
already arrested suspects in a series of bombings that rocked the
southern Philippine city of General Santos Saturday evening which
killed one woman and injured 36 persons.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at a press briefing in the city held by
mayor Adelbert Antonino along with Philippine National Police
chief Gen. Panfilo Lacson, according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Both Lacson and Antonino refused to divulge the suspects'
identities.
</P>
<P>
The suspects are now in the custody of the Criminal
Investigation and Detection Group for questioning, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Seven bombs exploded at several public facilities in General
Santos city on Saturday evening. The bombings began around 18:30
local time(10:30 GMT) with minutes apart between each blast. Some
of the bombs were put under vehicles.
</P>
<P>
One woman died on arrival upon being brought to the general
hospital in the city, and one of the injured, a five-year-old boy,
is in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Police said they have recovered several other unexploded bombs
in the city following the bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
Police also said they have been on alert since June 14 when
they received intelligence reports that the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front(MILF) will explode eight bombs in the city.
</P>
<P>
But MILF spokesman Eid Kabalu said the MILF has nothing to do
with the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Security has been intensified in the city where police closed
entries and exits after the bomb explosions.  
</P>
