<HEADLINE> Over 5,000 Clan Clash Survivors Starving in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (xinhua) -- Over 5,000 people including 720
school children are starving at El-Danaba in Mandela District in
northeastern Kenya after being displaced following clan feuds
between the Ajuran and Gare communities, local media reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The victims were among thousands of others who are currently
seeking refuge at Dandu, Gether and Takaba trading centers after
they were forcibly evicted from Bute sub-District three weeks ago,
the Sunday Standard and another newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that about 30 members of the Gare community have
been killed and 40 seriously injured in Bute sub-District while
others among them children have gone missing since the clashes
started.
</P>
<P>
The affected pastoralists, the majority from Gare clan, are
appealing for emergency food, water, medicine and shelter, and
asking the government to provide enough security for fear of
further attacks.
</P>
<P>
They said the government must act swiftly to address the
worsening situation in the area and claimed that the rival Ajuran
clan were harboring members of the Oromo Liberation Front, a
militia group opposed to the present Ethiopian government.
</P>
<P>
The victims also called on the government to appoint an
independent commission to investigate the presence of militias in
the area. 
</P>
