<HEADLINE> Two Main Indian Banks to Open Branches in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Two prominent Indian banks
are set to open up joint banking facilities in Tanzania in the
near future to promote economic relations between the two Indian
countries, local newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Indian High Commissioner to Tanzania Virendra Gupta told
local press here on Saturday that Bank of India and Bank of Baroda
have decided to get engaged in the joint venture and arrangements
were underway.
</P>
<P>
Gupta said there was growing interest among Indian businessmen
to invest in the banking sector in Tanzania and that his
government have always been encouraging them to do so.
</P>
<P>
"India is very impressed by Tanzania's macro-economic policies
and that it attaches a lot of importance to enhancing existing
economic relations between the two countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since a free market economy was introduced in Tanzania in early
1990s, several foreign banks have settled their branches,
including Trust Bank of Kenya, Commercial Bank of Kenya, STANBIC
of South Africa, CITI Bank of the United States, Standard
Chartered Bank of UK among others.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania was restructuring its state-owned banks in a bid to
make them profitable and to build a sound banking system in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, Tanzania sold its biggest commercial bank,
the National Bank of Commerce (1997) Limited, to the Amalgamated
Banks of South Africa Group (ABSA), with ABSA acquiring 70 percent
of the shares and Tanzanian government 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania admitted its failure to operate the bank profitably,
hoping it a success after the privatization which started in
November 1998 after the government split the National Bank of
Commerce into three entities in 1996, the National Micro-finance
Bank, the NBC (1997) and the NBC Holdings Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's central bank, Bank of Tanzania, has said that during
2000/ 2001 financial year, it would continue to strengthen its
supervisor capacity and improve on the reporting standards of the
commercial banks to minimize systemic failures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
