<HEADLINE> Congolese Official Explains Reason for Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Congolese Katanga Province director
Nyange Kangaza has said the Democratic Republic of the Congo civil
war might be forced to drag on because of its ethnic complexity,
Sunday Times of Zambia newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the visiting Congolese official as saying the war was
basically between the nilotics and the Bantu people with the
former harboring hegemonic ambitions to spread their influence in
the Great Lakes region as well as southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
Kangaza, who during the week paid a series of visits to the
border areas, said this at a cocktail party hosted for him by
Zambian Copperbelt Permanent Secretary Arthur Yoyo in Ndola,
capital of Copperbelt Province.
</P>
<P>
The civil war is being between President Laurent Kabila's
forces backed by Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola on one side and the
two factions of the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) supported
by Rwanda and Uganda on the other.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda is backing the main RCD rebel group based in Goma led by
Emile Ilunga while Uganda is supporting the Kisangani-based
faction of Wamba dia Wamba and Jean-Pierre Bemba's Congolese
Liberation movement (MLC).
</P>
<P>
But Rwanda and Uganda troops have since engaged in fierce
fighting over the control of the diamond trading city of Kisangani
in which more than 300 civilians are believed to have been killed
in the cross-fire.
</P>
<P>
"But I want you to understand that the war in the DRC is
between the nilotics and the Bantu. It is an expansionist war,"
Kangaza said.
</P>
<P>
He praised Zambian President Frederick Chiluba for the peace
initiative in the DRC saying peace was cardinal in the war-torn
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
