<HEADLINE> Xinhua Accuses Washington Times of Creating Rumors (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman with the Xinhua News
Agency today refuted reports by the Washington Times which tried
to discredit the news agency by making fuss about a normal real
estate transaction.
</P>
<P>
He accused the reports of "deliberately distorting the fact and
creating rumors with an intention to make trouble."
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the Washington Times has published
several reports since June 20 slandering the correspondents of
Xinhua's overseas bureaus of "being engaged in spying," and
claiming that the purchase of a new building by Xinhua's
Washington Bureau is aimed to "gather intelligence of the Pentagon.
"
</P>
<P>
"It is nothing but a rumor and smear. We are filled with great
indignation, and we strongly refute the reports," he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the current office of Xinhua's Washington
Bureau is in an apartment building on the North 14 Street,
Arlington, Virginia. Because the building is old and dilapidated
and the staff's working and living conditions are deteriorating,
the bureau decided to purchase a new office building at the
approval of the agency's headquarters in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Advised by American real estate agents, the bureau chose an
apartment building located at Arlington Ridge Road, Arlington, VA,
in early May 2000, formally informed the U.S. State Department of
the matter on May 22, and completed the needed procedures for the
legal purchase of the property with the aid of local lawyers on
June 15.
</P>
<P>
Like what had been done in the past, the purchase by the Xinhua
bureau was just a normal real estate deal done in conformity with
American laws, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency was established on November 7, 1931. With 8,
500 news subscribers, it now has 34 domestic bureaus and 104
overseas bureaus, and is regarded by the United Nations and the
international community as one of the biggest news agencies in the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Accuses Washington Times of Creating Rumors (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xinhua's mission is to report the major events in China and
around the world in an accurate, timely, objective and just manner,
to promote mutual understanding between the Chinese people and the
people of other countries, expand friendly cooperation and
safeguard world peace, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua's reports have aroused great interest and received warm
welcome worldwide, particularly, in developing countries, the
spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Xinhua's overseas correspondents have
always been strictly following laws of the countries they are
stationed in, and gathering news stories in accordance with local
regulations. "They have never been engaged in anything that is not
in conformity with their capacity of correspondents."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the spokesman, Xinhua correspondents
have established a profound friendship with people from various
circles in the countries they work in.
</P>
<P>
However, disregarding all the well-known facts, the Washington
Times has tried to discredit Xinhua by making fuss about a normal
real estate transaction, the spokesman said. Its reports are
against the basic professional ethics for newspaper men.
</P>
<P>
He said that we have noticed that the newspaper still sticks to
the Cold War mentality and often publishes reports that are
politically biased against China and the Chinese people. All this
is harmful to the development of the Sino-U.S. relationship as
well as the friendship between the people and journalists of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
"To safeguard the common interests of China and the United
States, we demand that the newspaper admit its mistake publicly
and hope it will never engage in such activities that go against
the professional ethics for newspaper men," the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
