<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Energy Output Down in Jan-Apr Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China's production of energy
dropped in the January-April period this year, according to the
latest figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total energy production in the first four months amounted to
295.06 million tons of standard coal equivalent, dipping 0.4
percent from the same 1999 period.
</P>
<P>
Production of coal dropped 6.0 percent to 254 million tons,
while that of gasoline surged 12.5 percent to 13.52 million tons.
</P>
<P>
During the period, China turned out 54.21 million tons of crude
oil, 2.9 percent more than in the same period last year. The
output of natural gas soared 12.6 percent to hit 9.06 billion
cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the output of electricity increased by 9.0
percent to 411.68 billion kwh. The output of thermal power
amounted to 347.90 billion kwh, up 4.9 percent year-on-year, and
that of hydro-electric power soared 42 percent to 58.46 billion
kwh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
