<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Passenger Traffic Rises, Freight Picks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China's passenger traffic
maintained steady growth in the first four months of 2000 with its
freight traffic picking up, according to figures released by the
National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total passenger traffic in the January-April period reached 4.
77 billion persons, 2.2 percent more than the same 1999 period.
</P>
<P>
The highway sector accounted for the bulk of the traffic volume,
with the number of passengers carried amounting to 4.34 billion,
up 1.8 percent year on year. The railway sector handled 348
million passengers, up 7.4 percent, and 20 million passengers
traveled by air during the period, up 10.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The waterway sector reported a decline in traffic, with the
number of passengers reaching 65 million, dipping 1.8 percent year
on year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, total freight traffic in the period reached 3.
99 billion tons, edging up 1.42 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The highway sector handled 3.09 billion tons of cargo, up 1.14
percent year-on-year; the railway sector, 530 million tons, up 3.
59 percent; the civil aviation sector, 584,400 tons, surging 15.76
percent; and the waterway sector, 372 million tons, up 0.73
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
