<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Dhaka, Washington Widely Split on TU Issue in EPZs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The outstanding issue of allowing
trade unions in the Export Processing Zones (EPZs) seems to be
dragging on, as Bangladesh and the United States recently
reiterated their contradictory stands.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Bangladeshi government finally decided not to
allow trade unions or union activities in the two EPZs, one at
Savar near the capital city Dhaka, and the other in the port city
Chittagong.
</P>
<P>
In an instant reaction to this decision, the U.S. authorities
have threatened to withdraw the Generalized System of Preference (
GSP) to Bangladesh, and issued an ultimatum to Bangladesh to
reverse the decision by August 15 or face an arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the Bangladeshi government has been in a very awkward
situation on the issue. On the hand, Japan and South Korea, major
investors in the EPZs, strongly oppose the existence of trade
unions, while on the other, the United States firmly asked for it.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean and Japanese industrialists have told
Bangladesh that they would start winding up their industrial units
once trade union is allowed.
</P>
<P>
Aiming at reaching a compromise between the investors, the
Bangladeshi government proposed to establish welfare associations
in the EPZs, trying to convince the U.S. that the associations
will protect the interest of the employees and workers.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the Bangladeshi government is
continuing talks with the United States in an effort to retain GSP
facility to Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"If the talks do not yield any positive result, then the
government will face the arbitration," an official said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, American Free Labor Union demanded that trade unions
be set up in the EPZs to protect workers' rights and implement
international labor laws.
</P>
<P>
Under the labor organization's pressure, the U.S. authorities
asked Bangladesh to allow trade unions in the EPZs as it did in
the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government replied that trade unions remained
prohibited since the establishment of EPZs and foreign investors
came in on condition of not allowing trade unions activities in
the zones to keep production unhindered.
</P>
<P>
Now the latest U.S. reaction poses a serious threat to the
country's export sector, particularly the ready-made garments
industry that earned as much as 1.8 billion U.S. dollars last year
alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Countries Urged to Focus on Similarities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Islamic countries should
focus on their similarities and not on their differences to build
on their respective achievements in various fields including in
economic and political areas, Malaysian Foreign Minister Syed
Hamid Albar said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"If politics haunts us in our efforts to achieve success, we
have to ease political tension and promote cooperation among us,"
he said in a program over Radio Television Malaysia (RTM), two
days before the opening of the four-day 27th meeting of the
Islamic Conference of Foreign Ministers here.
</P>
<P>
It is Malaysia's hope the meeting would have frank discussions
on these issues, Syed Hamid said, adding the conference would also
discuss, among others, ways of changing the western perception
that Islamic countries were backward and in constant conflict.
</P>
<P>
The conference would also look into ways to ensure that the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) member countries become
part of the respected international community and not seen as
countries involved in frequent bickering, he said.
</P>
<P>
Islamic countries need not be wholly dependent on other nations
because such total dependence would only cause a nation to be
easily controlled, Syed Hamid said, adding, "Hence, we have to
determine our own future."
</P>
<P>
On how the OIC could be more effective, the minister said
member countries must conduct self-appraisal to gauge their
strength and weaknesses and tap their available resources for
their common benefit.
</P>
<P>
"I think to suggest that the OIC has not achieved anything is
not true. Unlike before, we know each other more now with
increased cooperation among us, bilateral relations have been
established and these must be enhanced," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there should not be any doubt on the OIC'S capability
to function effectively for the benefit of Muslim nations.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 delegates from OIC-member countries will attend the
foreign ministers' meeting which begins here on June 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian FM on Int'l Financial Structure Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Syed Hamid Albar said Sunday that Malaysia's proposal to move a
resolution on the international financial architecture reforms at
the forthcoming Islamic Conference of Foreign Ministers is not
aimed at taking over from the World Bank or the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
What Malaysia wishes to see is both the rich and developing
countries jointly make efforts to strengthen the world financial
system, he said in a program over Radio Television Malaysia (RTM)
prior to the opening of the four-day 27th meeting of the Islamic
Foreign Ministers here on June 27.
</P>
<P>
He said "The IMF anecdote for the financial ills is the same
for all. Some will have to die as their complaints differed. Hence,
we have to diagnose the other problems as well."
</P>
<P>
As such, the minister said, in the formulation of the new
financial architecture, the sensitivities and the prevailing
situations should be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
"We also need to consider capital flow, currency manipulations
and regulatory requirements which work against the weak nations
that could not by themselves face the world financial giants,"
Syed Hamid said.
</P>
<P>
He said that apart from proposals to enhance multilateral
trading and a new financial architecture, Malaysia would also make
suggestions on the advancement of technology and communication
within the OIC.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 delegates from OIC-member countries are expected to
attend the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
