<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Praises Voting Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Saturday said the huge voter turnout and peace that marked the
start of the two-day parliamentary election showed that democracy
is getting stronger.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after touring his house in Harare, Mugabe
said, " This is a very important election. I hope it goes well.
I can see and feel it is very quiet, people are voting massively.
 Whites are also voting massively, I do not know how they are
voting but I hope it's positive."
</P>
<P>
"It's a message that the democratic process is strengthening in
 Zimbabwe and I hope it keeps strengthening," he said.
</P>
<P>
After a helicopter tour of most constituencies in Harare and
other provinces, Chairman of the Election Directorate Mariyawanda
Nzuwah said voting started on high note as tens of thousands of
people turned out to cast their votes at all polling stations
throughout the country on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
If Saturday's huge turn-out was maintained throughout the
country, most people would have exercised their right to vote
when polling ends Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri said the election was
held in a peaceful environment Saturday as no incidents of
violence had been reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of the European Union election observer mission Pierre
Schori is impressed by the way the country's parliamentary
elections are being conducted.
</P>
<P>
"He told President Mugabe that he had the opportunity to go to
some polling stations in Harare in the morning and was impressed
by the professionalism at the voting centers," government sources
said.
</P>
<P>
He added the EU has been working well with Zimbabwe since
independent in 1980 and wanted to continue on the path. 
</P>
</TEXT>
