<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President to Meet Rwandan Counterpart Kagame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
will meet his Rwandan counterpart Paul Kagame over the recent
clashes in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the New
Vision daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Museveni who was speaking on CBS radio to the live Luganda
Program, local language program, did not say when and where they
would meet, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There has been no war between Uganda and Rwanda but clashes, he
said, adding that he did not consider Rwanda as an enemy and that
they have achieved what they had wanted to have withdrawn their
troops from the Congolese city of Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
He said the 28 soldiers of the Uganda People's Defence Forces
(UPDF) who Rwanda refers to as POWs are mostly those who were in
the U.N. company, and not were captured from Tchopo bridge in
Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Observer team in Congo had borrowed 216 officers and men
from the UPDF for security reason in Kisangani after a ceasefire
was agreed and withdrawal from the city started following clashes
between the Ugandan and Rwandan troops in Kisangani where they
shelled each other two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said Uganda did not go to DRC to interfere, but to
defend itself and this has resulted in the development of Western
Uganda following the demolishing of rebel bases of the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) in eastern DRC.
</P>
<P>
The president said among the benefits for having gone to DRC
was that UPDF had managed to break the back of the ADF rebels.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper report, Museveni said Uganda would
talk about the Kisangani reparations when it goes to the Hague to
put up its defence against the case filed by the DRC President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
He said Kabila would be put to task to explain why his country
has remained unstable and a haven for wrong elements that even
destabilize neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
