<HEADLINE> U.S. Diplomats in Row With New Sri Lankan Party  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Three U.S. diplomats including the
Deputy Head of Mission have walked out of a meeting in a dispute
with the new Sri Lankan political party, Sinhala Urumaya (Heritage)
, the Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The row took place when the Colombo-based U.S. diplomats
questioned the party leader S.L. Gunasekara regarding the "
genocide" by the Sri Lankan forces in the north and the minority
rights and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Gunasekara in return questioned the U.S. diplomats on the issue
of bombing of Hiroshima and genocide by U.S. forces and the
minority rights and human rights in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Heated words were exchanged at the time and the three diplomats
walked out abruptly, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held at the residence of Gunasekara.
</P>
<P>
Sinhala Urumaya, established on April 26 this year, is a
nationalist party which aims to safeguard the rights of the
majority Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists forming 74 percent of
the 19 million population.
</P>
<P>
The party opposes giving special status to the Tamils who are
generally Hindus making up 18 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
It claims that Sri Lanka doesn't have an ethnic problem, but a
terrorist problem, which should be solved militarily.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, alleging
the Sinhalese government discriminates against the Tamils, are
fighting for a homeland for the Tamils in the country's north and
east since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
