<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Makes Remarkable Achievements in Drug Fight  By Duan Tingchang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The "Golden Triangle" area
bordering Myanmar, Thailand and Laos is the main base where opium
and heroin are produced.
</P>
<P>
For many years, narcotic drugs have not only run rampant there
but also been illegally smuggled to every part of the world.
</P>
<P>
In face of the grave danger brought to Myanmar and the
international community, Myanmar has launched anti-drug battles
year by year and has scored remarkable achievements.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by Myanmar's Central
Committee for Drug Abuse Control (CCDAC), during the 12 years
between 1988 and 1999 and with the cooperation of its army units,
police force and customs departments, Myanmar exposed over 50,000
drug-related cases, arrested over 70,000 drug offenders, seized 29,
833 kilos of opium, 4,448 kilos of heroin, 6,880 kilos of
marijuana, 503,528 liters of precursor chemicals and 55.89 million
tablets of stimulants, and destroyed 110 heroin refineries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, during the period, Myanmar also destroyed 37,379
hectares of poppy cultivation, resulting in reduction of 400 tons
of opium output annually.
</P>
<P>
Of the 32,794 kilos of drugs destroyed, heroin accounted for 3,
679 kilos, while opium represented 23,646 kilos. The destruction
also included 24.26 million tablets of stimulant drugs.
</P>
<P>
In April 1997, there established a "drug-free" zone in Mongla
region, eastern part of Shan state.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there is now a total of 86,
537 drug addicts in Myanmar. To help them give up drug addictions
and regain health, the Myanmar government has set up six treatment
centers in Yangon, Mandalay, Myitkyina,Taunggyi, Lashio and Kyaing
Tong, catering to 2,000 addicts annually.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country also established eight rehabilitation
centers under the Social Welfare Department for ex-addicts.
</P>
<P>
Due to efforts of years, Myanmar's poppy cultivated area and
drug production dropped markedly. The Myanmar CCDAC said, in 1999,
the country's poppy cultivated area reduced by 31 percent as
compared with 1998, while its drug production dropped by 38
percent from the same year.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate its achievement made in drug control and to
educate people on the danger of drugs and to stay away from them,
Myanmar is building two drug control museums.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Myanmar has reached memorandums of understanding on
regional drug control action plan with China, Cambodia, Laos,
Thailand and Vietnam. It also signed agreements on bilateral
cooperation in drug control with India, Bangladesh, Vietnam,
Russia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Another measure is increasing of investment in drug-cultivating
and producing border areas and minorities-inhabited areas to raise
their living standard and change their traditional way of
livelihood which depends on drug cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Although Myanmar has made big achievements in drug eradication,
due to domestic security and problems in international assistance,
the success is not as anticipated.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has started in 1999 implementing a 15-year plan worth
255 million U.S. dollars, aimed at total elimination of drugs
covering 51 cultivating and producing townships.
</P>
<P>
In order to realize the aim as early as possible, Myanmar has
urged the international community to enhance cooperation, and
moreover, to further extend aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communal Clash Continues in Maluku, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Communal violence between
Christians and Muslims continued to torment the riot-stricken
Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku province, according to
reports reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The latest clashes in Talake and Galala subdistricts on
Saturday left at least 10 people dead and 36 injured, bringing the
death toll in the four days of continuous fierce fighting to 41.
</P>
<P>
Around 6,000 people, mostly women and children from the
subdistricts of Halong, Galala, Poka and Rumah Tiga, have poured
into the Halong Naval Base, 12 kilometers east of Ambon, in panic
since the new round of rioting began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ambon, about 2,300 kilometers east of Jakarta, was totally
paralyzed as the two warring parties attacked each other with
grenades and mortars. Heavy rain during the night was not enough
to stop their actions, which continued late into Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides have sent children and women to safer areas, while
men stay to protect their properties," a resident of Bata Merah
subdistrict was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Maluku police chief Brigadier General Dewa Astika Saturday said
it would be difficult to block the rioters as some members of the
security forces, both police and military, had taken sides with
one of the warring camps.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, at least 152 persons died in religious violence in
Halmahera island, North Maluku province. It was one of the worst
incidents in nearly two years of religious and ethnic violence
that has plagued Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to calm down the situation, Indonesian Military (TNI)
Commander Admiral Widodo A.S. Saturday voiced support for the
government to declare a state of emergency in Maluku and North
Maluku provinces.
</P>
<P>
Widodo said TNI would soon take tough measures to stop the
widespread violence and would conduct door-to-door sweeping
operations to confiscate unlicensed weapons.
</P>
<P>
"TNI will take stern measures in anticipating further
developments. There will be also a concentration of troops in
several riot-prone places to prevent clashes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Widodo's support for a state of emergency in ravaged provinces
came just one day after President Abdurrahman Wahid announced the
closure of the two provinces to outsiders due to escalating
destruction there.
</P>
<P>
Maluku and North Maluku provinces have witnessed nearly two
years of religious and ethnic violence. The number of people
killed and wounded in both provinces now runs into thousands.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that tensions in the two provinces have been
fueled by the arrival of 2,000 hard-line Muslim fighters from Java
island, who have vowed a holy war. Their leaders have said they
would not wage a war against Christians, but help fellow Muslims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
