<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Opposition May Resign en Masse From House of Representatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Thai major opposition party the
New Aspiration Party (NAP) resolved to resign en masse from
parliament to pressure the government into dissolving the House of
Representatives and holding a snap election, according to the
latest television broadcast Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, it was unclear how many of NAP's 116 members of
parliament (MPs) would actually follow the call of their executive
committee.
</P>
<P>
After a four-hour meeting of the committee Saturday, NAP leader
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh read out a statement saying his party wanted
to return power to the people.
</P>
<P>
The government could not effectively perform its duty in
parliament and resigning was the only way to stop the government
from furthering damaging the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The response to the executive committee's resolution remained
uncertain. The decision is to be formally put to the party's MPs
on Tuesday and they are supposed to tender their resignation to
parliament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Chavalit's faction has only 55 MPs. Another 50 are in the
Wang Nam Yen faction of Sanoh Thienthong and 11 others are
defecting to Chart Pattana.
</P>
<P>
It is not known if Sanoh, who was unceremoniously booted out of
the secretary-general's job by Chavalit and is moving to Thai Rak
Thai Party, will abide by the decision.
</P>
<P>
The 11 MPs moving to the coalition Chart Pattana Party have
already made it known they will not resign.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the government would
keep doing its job despite the NAP's decision.
</P>
<P>
Foremost in the government's mind was the budget bill for
fiscal 2001, due for deliberation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If the NAP opted not to resign, the prime minister is bound by
law to propose its leader as the new opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
Sathit Wongnongtoey, the ruling Democrat spokesman, admitted
the NAP's departure would have an effect on the government, but
how much of a problem it causes would depend on how many MPs
actually resign on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The six-party ruling coalition, taking power in late 1997, has
237 seats in the 385-member parliament. It must call a general
election before November when its term expires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
