<HEADLINE> Fiji's Coup Leader Frees Four Female Hostages EDS-Adds Details, Coup Group's New Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's coup leader George Speight
has released the four women hostages and said the remaining
hostages will not be freed until a new president is sworn in, the
Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) reported Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Speight and his group released the women without any warning
Saturday night, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
There is no indication when he will release the remaining 27
men.
</P>
<P>
All four are said to be in good health, but will undergo
medical check-ups at the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The women, three of whom were MPs, were briefing other families
about the health of the remaining 27 hostages and may be available
to speak publicly later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Speight group has given an ultimatum to the
military that it will not release the remaining hostages until
after a president is installed, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
The Muanikau Accord, an agreement to end Fiji's five-week-old
hostage crisis which had been scheduled to be signed on Saturday,
stipulated that all hostages should walk free within three hours
of its signing.
</P>
<P>
But the Speight group now said a president must be sworn in
first.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Fiji's hostage talks ended in deadlock and a
military official said a new attempt to reach agreement would
start on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Military spokesman Filipo Tarakinikini said Saturday that talks
on the release of the 31 hostages held in parliament by Speight's
group had stalled over the issue of the future presidency of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
