<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``Majority of Dunhuang Sutra Cave Relics Kept in Foreign Countries" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The corrupt government of late Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) did not
have the ability to protect the relics, and a large number of hand-
copied and printed sutras, exquisite embroidery objects, colored
sculptures and documents were stolen.
</P>
<P>
According to scholars, China currently preserves 18,500 items
of Dunhuang relics; Russia, 19,000 pieces; Britain, 13,300; France,
6,000; Japan, 1,000; the United States, 25; Denmark, 16; and
Germany, three.
</P>
<P>
Dunhuang relics are also being kept in India, Finland, the
Republic of Korea, Australia and Sweden, experts said.
</P>
<P>
In China, Dunhuang relics are mainly stored in 30 museums and
libraries in Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Nanjing, Gansu, and
Taiwan, including the Beijing Library, the Beijing University
Library, the Palace Museum and the National Central Library in
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Library alone houses 16,000 items of Dunhuang
relics, and 144 are kept in the National Central Library in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
China has been collecting Dunhuang relics ever since the
founding the People's Republic of China in 1949, but many are
still missing, said Fan Jinshi, director of the Institute of the
Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
The institute is actively seeking ways to gather the lost
Dunhuang relics through donations or purchase, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a Japanese donated eight Dunhuang relics kept by his
family, becoming the first foreigner to voluntarily return
Dunhuang relics to China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts hope that his action will inspire more
foreigners and foreign governments to return Dunhuang treasures to
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``Majority of Dunhuang Sutra Cave Relics Kept in Foreign Countries" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUNHUANG (Gansu Province), June 25 (Xinhua) -- A total of 57,
794 items of relics have been discovered so far in the Sutra Cave
at the world-famous Mogao Grottoes in northwest China's Gansu
Province, much more than the widely reported 50,000, Chinese
scholars said. However, the majority of the relics are now being
kept in a dozen foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have called for the return of the Dunhuang
relics kept by foreign countries to China during the ongoing
series of activities to mark the 100th anniversary of the
discovery of the Sutras Cave.
</P>
<P>
The dispersal of Dunhuang relics, including Buddhist sculptures,
documents, paintings and embroidery dating from the 4th to the
11th centuries is not only regrettable for Chinese historical
studies, but also regrettable as far as human civilization is
concerned, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
According to scholars at the Institute of Dunhuang Studies in
Gansu, many relics found in the cave are scattered in 13 countries-
- China, Britain, France, Russia, Japan, the United States,
Germany, Denmark, India, Finland, the Republic of Korea, Australia
and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The Sutra Cave was reportedly accidentally found by a Taoist
priest when he was clearing sand from the No. 16 grotto on June 22,
1900.
</P>
<P>
The cave, containing the relics from a dozen dynasties, offers
valuable materials for the study of the history, geography,
religion, economy, politics, culture, nationalities, literature,
arts and science and technology of ancient China and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the cave, considered one of China's four major
archaeological discoveries in the 20th century, created its own
branch of learning -- Dunhuang Studies.
</P>
<P>
The discovery, eye-catching worldwide since that time,
attracted many adventurers and explorers from Russia, Britain, the
United States, Japan and other countries to the Mogao Grottoes. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Regional News In China (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHEJIANG: The Longwan District in the city of Wenzhou, has
become the largest artificial leather production base in the
country. The district has more than 40 artificial leather
enterprises, which turn out goods worth more than 500 million yuan
a year, 40 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
YUNNAN: China has begun construction of its largest botanical
garden in Xishuangbanna. This is another major step adopted by
China to protect its diversified biological resources. The garden
will collect plants species from tropical and subtropical zones
worldwide and protect endangered species.
</P>
<P>
SICHUAN: A ship carrying more than 200 passengers sank on a
section of the Yangtze River near Luzhou in southwest China's
Sichuan Province on June 22. Rescuers retrieved 13 bodies and
saved 51 other passengers that day, and search is continuing along
the river for survivors and bodies.
</P>
<P>
GUIZHOU: The province plans to build a museum on medicine
resources in Guiyang, the provincial capital. The museum will
mainly exhibit traditional Chinese medicine and also collect and
exhibit traditional medicines from various ethnic groups in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
