<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Regional News In China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN: This north China port city has basically completed the
construction of a new harbor area covering five square kilometers.
The project involved a total investment of two billion yuan (about
360 million U.S. dollars). The new harbor area will have a
handling capacity of 20.5 million tons of cargo when it is
completed next year.
</P>
<P>
The city has also risen to become the biggest trading center of
ceramics products in north China, with an annual ceramics trading
turnover of more than five billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
SHANGHAI: In an unprecedented scale, Shanghai plans to recruit
500 postdoctoral researchers this year. At present, 48 local
agencies have a total of 109 postdoctoral research stations.
</P>
<P>
This city, China's largest metropolis, is set to control the
population of permanent residents within 16 million by the year
2010, and the birth rate of permanent residents will be targeted
at 9.6 per thousand by that year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is expected to host China's first web fair on August
22-25. The China Web Fair will focus on Internet business,
solutions for enterprises going on-line, and Web security.
</P>
<P>
GUANGDONG: A total of 633 smuggled cars were seized from
January to May this year by Gongbei Customs in this southern China
province near Macao and Hong Kong. These cars are worth 22.38
million yuan (2.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A fair for Chinese students studying abroad will be held in
Guangzhou, capital of south Guangdong Province, from December 28
to 30. The fair, the third of its kind, will highlight high and
new technological achievements made by Chinese students studying
abroad, and exchange of outstanding talents.
</P>
