<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Regional News In China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEILONGJIANG: Six ethnic gene banks have been established in
the Harbin Medical Sciences University. The genes of six ethnic
minority groups including the Mongolian and the Xibo are currently
frozen in liquefied nitrogen at minus 273 degrees Celsius,
awaiting for deciphering.
</P>
<P>
SHAANXI: The world's first goat which was cloned from adult
body cells, died of breathing failure caused by defects in lung
development in the early morning of June 18 after living 36 hours
and three minutes. The goat, named "Yuanyuan," was cloned by
researchers of Northwest University of Science and Technology for
Agriculture and Forestry in northwest Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Four days later, the second goat cloned from adult goat body
cells was born on June 22. The second goat, named "Yangyang", is
33.5-cm long and 29.5-cm tall, and weighs 2.6 kg.
</P>
<P>
GANSU: Chinese archaeologists have discovered excerpts from the
Christian Bible written in an ancient Syrian language in the
northern zone of the Mogao Grottoes of Dunhuang in northwest Gansu
Province.
</P>
<P>
QINGHAI: Chinese archaeologists have discovered a site of Qijia
Culture in northwest China's Qinghai Province. The Qijia Culture
flourished in the transition period from the Neolithic Age to the
Bronze Age, some 3,500 to 4,000 years ago. The ruins are located
in Lajia Village, Minhe County, on the upper reaches of the Yellow
River, believed to be the first of its kind ever found in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
