<HEADLINE> One Malaysian Hostage Freed by Abu Sayyaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Muslim extremist group Abu
Sayyaf Saturday released one Malaysian of the 21 hostages it held
on Jolo island in the southern Philippines, the biggest break so
far in the hostage crisis which entered its third month.
</P>
<P>
Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado said that no
ransom was paid and no political promises were made in the release
of Zulkurmain Bin Hashim, 29, who is now under the custody of
Aventajado, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Aventajado called the release "a gesture of goodwill" by the
Abu Sayyaf group, which is still holding captive three Germans,
two French, two Finns, two South Africans, one Lebanese, eight
other Malaysians and two Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were kidnapped by Abu Sayyaf rebels on April 23
from the diving resort of Sipadan in neighboring Malaysia. The
Malaysians and Filipinos are staff members on the resort.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf had demanded for the setting up of an
independent Islamic state in Mindanao, a total ban on commercial
fishing in the Sulu Sea and the formation of a commission between
the Philippines and Malaysia to address the alleged maltreatment
of some 500,000 Filipino Muslims living in Malaysia's Sabah state.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group had also demanded a ransom of one million U.S.
dollars for each of its captives.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has repeatedly ruled out any breakup
of the country and stuck to its no-ransom policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unexploded Bombs Found in General Santos City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Police authorities said they have
recovered several other unexploded bombs in General Santos City
after seven bombs exploded in the southern Philippine city
Saturday evening, which killed one woman and wounded 36 others.
</P>
<P>
Police said they have been on alert since June 14 when they
received intelligence reports that the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front will explode eight bombs in the city, according to a report
of the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The series of bombings began around 18:30 local time (10:30 GMT)
with minutes apart between each blast. Some of the bombs were
placed under vehicles.
</P>
<P>
One woman, identified Elena Kabasag, died on arrival upon being
brought to the general hospital in the city, and one of the
injured, a five-year-old boy, is in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Police said those responsible for the bombings used pipe bombs
and magnetic bombs which were powerful enough to destroy
structures and kill people as they were made of mortar shells
attached to an explosive.
</P>
<P>
So far, no individual or group has claimed responsibility for
the bombings. Police have blocked entries and exits of the city.
</P>
<P>
The report said two blasts were at the vicinity of the public
market, one blast at the parking lot of Gaisano Mall, one along
Magsaysay Avenue, another one in front of Safii Hardware Store.
</P>
<P>
The blast also rocked several city bank branches - Metrobank,
Land Bank and PCI Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
