<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Predict Decreased Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have predicted
that China's exports will slow down in the second half of this
year while imports are expected to increase quickly, according to
today's Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes Long Guoqiang with the Development Research
Center of the State Council as saying that the high rate of
increase in exports in the first half was based on a comparatively
low base last year, and the growth is expected to slow in July.
</P>
<P>
He said a declining trend can already be detected -- the May
increase, 27.1 percent compared to last May, was lower than rates
for the first four months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Imports, however, may continue to grow because of the
strengthening economy and expanding investment, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Experts also believe that there is "room for improvement" in
policies affecting imports and exports, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months, China's trade volume surged 36.1
percent from comparable months of last year to 174.1 billion U.S.
dollars with a surplus of 10.5 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use Special Ink to Protect Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China will soon use optically
variable ink (OVI) in producing its Renminbi currency, which will
enable people to pick out a fake 100 yuan note at a glance.
</P>
<P>
The ink will make colors of the note change from light green to
darker green or nearly black when viewed from different angles,
according to today's Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that China has focused on the development of
high-tech banknote printing and minting in recent years to "
enhance the safety of the Renminbi."
</P>
<P>
The use of the technology will make China the third country in
the world that can produce this special ink after Switzerland and
the United States, the paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
