<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tour de France Urine Samples to be Frozen for Future EPO Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Urine samples from riders in this
year's Tour de France are to be frozen and tested for the banned
substance EPO (erythropoietine) when a reliable method for
detecting the drug has been perfected, the International Cycling
Union (UCI) confirmed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
UCI president Hein Verbruggen approved the measure following
Thursday's decision not to validate a new method for detecting the
drug, developed by the French National Anti-Doping Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
Two of the experts examining the new procedure demanded that
further aspects be examined before the total validation of the
method.
</P>
<P>
Verbruggen said Saturday that he was optimistic about the
future of the test and that although it would not be ready for the
July 1-23 Tour urine samples would be frozen and "conserved under
the required conditions".
</P>
<P>
A UCI statement said that the decision had been taken in order
to ensure that this year's Tour ran smoothly and peacefully. "We
believe the method could be finally validated in the coming months.
If an analysis later shows up positive for EPO, rules and
sanctions can still be applied," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
EPO causes the body to create more blood cells, bringing more
oxygen to muscles and enabling them to work longer and harder. It
thus can boost performance by 10 percent or more. But the drug is
extremely difficult to detect.
</P>
<P>
Since it started being used by athletes in the 1980's 26
cyclists and several elite athletes have died in suspicious
circumstances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
