<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wimbledon May Change Seeding System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- All England Tennis Club may change
the seeding system in next year's Wimbledon championships after
complaints from some players that the system was not objective,
club chairman Tim Phillips said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said Wimbledon and ATP Tour officials would work closely
together to reconcile the differences in their approach to the
seedings in time for next year's tournament, according to a
Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
The ATP Tour Entry System used to work out players world
rankings is adjusted by the All England Club's Order of Play
Committee, which determines the seedings at Wimbledon, to "better
reflect player skills on grass".
</P>
<P>
The club says its separate set of criteria recognize the
special nature of grass court play.
</P>
<P>
Phillips said the need to reassess the criteria had come about
because this was the first year the players had to count the
points they won at Wimbledon in their ATP Tour rankings.
</P>
<P>
"This important change has highlighted the differences in
primary objectives of the two different approaches to seeding,"
said Phillips.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Spanish players Alex Corretja, Juan Carlos Ferrero
and Albert Costa threatened to boycott Wimbledon because they had
not been seeded.
</P>
<P>
The three clay court specialists wrote to the ATP Tour
complaining that the All England Club had ignored their world
rankings and excluded them from the seedings.
</P>
<P>
Corretja is ranked 11th, Ferrero 13th and Costa 15th according
to the ATP Tour Entry System used by all other tournaments.
</P>
<P>
Ferrero withdrew from the championships on Saturday with a
lower back injury.
</P>
<P>
The ATP sent an observer to this year's seedings meeting in
order better to understand Wimbledon's approach.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied that they conscientiously endeavoured to
select seeds based on their grass court credentials," said Mark
Miles, the ATP Tour's Chief Executive Officer.
</P>
<P>
Miles said he recognized the special circumstances involved
with playing on grass and the difficulties this produces in the
seeding process. But he added that, "... any subjective system
must be open to criticism."
</P>
<P>
"For the betterment of the game, and in fairness to all players,
I am pleased that both organizations (Wimbledon and the ATP) are
committed to working out an equitable arrangement to resolve these
issues for next year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
