<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Resolve Sharia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government said Sunday
that it would soon effectively resolve the crisis over the
controversial Islamic law of Sharia which has been introduced in
four northern states.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is being very carefully studied and we will
resolve it in the interest of all Nigerians," said Information
Minister Jerry Gana in a Lagos radio interview.
</P>
<P>
"We have the solution, but we want to do it in such a way that
when applied, it will be effective," Gana said. He did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The controversy over Sharia has resurfaced following the
introduction of the Koran-based law last Wednesday in Kano state
after Zamfara, Niger and Sokoto.
</P>
<P>
More states in the predominantly Muslim northern Nigeria are
under pressure to follow suit. Christians, living mostly in the
southern part of the country, described the introduction of Sharia
as unconstitutional in secular Nigeria. They have urged the
federal government to seek constitutional clarification at the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The government has refused to do so but allowed individuals and
 organizations whose interests were affected by Sharia to go to
court.
</P>
<P>
The controversy broke into a bloody clash in February between
Moslems and Christians in the northern city of Kaduna, leaving
more than 1,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The deaths sparked off reprisal killings in the country's
southeastern part, and forced governors in the areas to call for
confederacy in the country.
</P>
<P>
To ease the tension, the federal government and governors of
the 19 northern states later reached an agreement to suspend the
implementation of Sharia and return to the existing penal code.
</P>
<P>
Niger, Sokoto and Kano states have since introduced the Sharia
in violation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
But Gana assured all Nigerians Saturday that the government had
the courage, vision and determination to resolve the issue and
ensure peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government was cautious in its intervention
because " issues of religion are very emotive and if not well
handled can lead to a situation that last for years". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Court Orders Shell to Pay Compensation for Oil Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A court in Nigeria' s southeastern
city of Port Harcourt has ordered the oil giant Royal Dutch and
Shell Cooperation to pay about 40 million U.S. dollars in
compensation for a 1970 oil spill in the area, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported on Sunday. The agency quoted a Shell spokesman
in Lagos as saying on Sunday that the court passed the verdict on
Friday and that the company's Nigerian unit, Shell Petroleum
Development Company (SPDC), was appealing.
</P>
<P>
"We can confirm that a Rivers State High Court in Port Harcourt
 delivered judgment in a case arising from the 1970 oil spill at
Ebubu, Rivers State, and awarded four billion naira (about 40
million dollars) against SPDC," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The case has been dragging since the Ejamaa Ebubu community
near Port Harcourt went to court nine years ago seeking
compensation for the spill, which devastated an area in the Ogoni
region whose people have been battling Shell for alleged
exploitation and ecological damage.
</P>
<P>
Villagers and witnesses say the mangrove swamp area where the
spill occurred has been covered by a thick crust of oil that is
now as hard as asphalt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
