<DOCNO> XIE20000625.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac, Schroeder Support Majority Decision in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, June 25 (Xinhua)--German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
and visiting French President Jacques Chirac Sunday said they
wanted more decision by majority in the European Union (EU) to
raise its ability of operation.
</P>
<P>
At a joint interview in Hanover with German ZDF television,
the two leaders also supported the EU's eastward enlargement.
</P>
<P>
"I am in full agreement with the French President, that we
must create more possibility for majority decision," said
Schroeder, adding, "Germany and France will not split over this
issue."
</P>
<P>
Chirac also said the issue "will not be a problem."
</P>
<P>
In present EU decision-making mechanism, each of the 15 member
countries owns veto power. Germany has been calling for decision
by majority in the bloc, but smaller countries are afraid of
losing their impacts on the EU policy under majority voting system.
</P>
<P>
The necessity of a majority decision has become undeniable,"
said Schroeder, "When Europe is larger, we must have it to keep
Europe's ability to operate."
</P>
<P>
About the EU's eastward enlargement, Chirac said France would
achieve progress during its term of EU rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
"I am ambitious to go on with this adventure with progress,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Paris is due to take over the half-year EU rotating presidency
from Portugal on July 1st.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder agreed with Chirac's viewpoint and said the EU's
eastward enlargement was also accordance with national interests.
"We will not only give, but also get," he said.
</P>
<P>
But neither of the two spelled out a concrete date when the EU
would accept new members, such as Poland, Hungary, and Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a political decision," stressed Chirac, adding that
the candidates must continue "necessary economic reform."
</P>
<P>
"One must be in the position at first to become a member of
the Union. One must be in the position to apply the rules of the
game," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Over the EU's troubled relation with Austria, both Chirac and
Schroeder rejected to loosen the EU's boycott against Austria. "At
the present there is no ground to think about that," said
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
The two also support a common immigrants law of the EU.
Schroeder said the problem should be solved in middle term, Chirac
agreed and added, in one or two years there should be a common
European law.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Schroeder said that France, Germany and Finland
were closely co-operating to solve the hostage crisis in
Philippine. Both vowed to "take every thoughtful step to free the
hostage."
</P>
<P>
"We are trying our best. We are heartily concerned at the
crisis," said Chirac, but adding there was nothing harder to solve
than the kidnapping crisis. Schroeder also said, "we need patience.
"
</P>
<P>
The Philippine anti-government forces kidnapped 21 foreigners,
including Germans, Frenchmen, and Finns as hostage this April. The
EU has intervened in the negotiations aiming to free the hostage,
but no progress has been made till now.
</P>
<P>
Before this joint interview, the first families of Germany and
France had dinner together in a Hanover restaurant. Chirac is due
to arrive in Berlin to formally begin his German trip Monday noon,
after he visits the Expo 2000 world fair in Hanover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
